%N A389256 Total number of increasing runs in all heapable permutations of length n.
%C A389256 A permutation of [1..n] is heapable if it can be inserted, one element at a time, into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A389256 An increasing run in a permutation is a maximal contiguous subsequence that is strictly increasing.
%H A389256 Benjamin Chen, Michael Cho, Mario Tutuncu-Macias, and Tony Tzolov, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dam.2023.01.025">Efficient methods of calculating the number of heapable permutations</a>, Discrete Applied Mathematics Volume 331, 31 May 2023, Pages 126-137.
%H A389256 Manolopoulos Panagiotis, <a href="/A389256/a389256.py.txt">Python program</a>.
%e A389256 For n=4, the heapable permutations are:
%e A389256   (1,2,3,4): runs (1,2,3,4) => 1 increasing run.
%e A389256   (1,3,2,4): runs (1,3)(2,4) => 2 increasing runs.
%e A389256   (1,2,4,3): runs (1,2,4)(3) => 2 increasing runs.
%e A389256   (1,4,2,3): runs (1,4)(2,3) => 2 increasing runs.
%e A389256   (1,3,4,2): runs (1,3,4)(2) => 2 increasing runs.
%e A389256 So among the 5 heapable permutations of length 4:
%e A389256   1 permutation has 1 increasing run,
%e A389256   4 permutations have 2 increasing runs,
%e A389256   for a total of 9 increasing runs.
%Y A389256 Cf. A336282 (number of heapable permutations), A386382 (for runs), A389232 (for decreasing runs).
